ce:section.ce:para:
In order to explore charge transfer mechanisms, surface passivation, and interfacial charging separation, as well as investigate corrosion or barriers at the electrolyte-metal interface, EIS is regarded as a non-destructive electrochemical testing approach [41,42]. The frequency response derived from EIS is shown using Nyquist and Bode plots [65]. In the EIS method, the Nyquist plot is obtained by plotting real impedance versus imaginary impedances. The Bode plot is comprised of two plots: a magnitude plot and a phase angle plot that, respectively, displays the frequency response's amplitude and phase shift. The Nyquist and Bode plot obtained for only corrosive solution i.e. for 3.5 wt% NaCl solution without inhibitor has been presented in Fig. 1
(a,b). The simple characteristic depressed semicircle that the Nyquist plot displays in the blank solution is most likely caused by the charge transfer resistance that results from the corrosion product's deposition on the steel surface and the inability of these corrosion products to provide high corrosion protection performance. As a result, in the absence of an inhibitor, charge transfer resistance (
R
ct
), diffuse layer resistance (
R d
), and accumulation resistance (
R a
) all contribute to resistance formed at the metal/solution interface. Essentially, polarization resistance (
R p
) can be defined as all of these resistances combined and represented collectively. As a result, the polarization resistance is the difference between the higher and lower frequencies in the real axis [10,14,66–68]. A simple electrical equivalent circuit comprised (vide Fig. 1 c) of solution resistance (Rs), in series with a polarization resistance (
R p
), and parallel to a constant phase element (CPE), have been utilized to fit the Nyquist plot of the blank sample [69–71]. The Nyquist and Bode plot by subsequent addition of different concentrations of CI@Cd-MOF (vide Fig. 2
a, b, c) and CI@Zn-MOF (vide Fig. 3
a, b, c) have also shown and related electrochemical parameters of EIS measurement of each experiment have been tabulated in Table 1
. After the addition of inhibitors, every resulting Nyquist plot consisted of two capacitive loops that represented the charge transfer and relaxation processes. The impedance plot displayed a semicircular-like arc because the two capacitive arcs are identical and superimposed to each other due to their shared time constant [6,69]. As a result, the electrical equivalent circuit (vide Fig. 1 d) used to fit the Nyquist plots consisted of solution resistance (Rs) coupled in series with a two-time constant: Inhibitor film resistance (Rf) and inhibitor film capacitance (Qf) are the components of the first block, while charge transfer resistance (Rct) and double layer capacitance (Qdl) are the components of the second block [6,14,72]. When CI@Cd-MOF and CI@Zn-MOF have been added, the capacitive arc's diameter significantly increased, indicating that these inhibitors successfully adsorb to the steel surface and minimize corrosion. The diameter has been observably widening as the inhibitor concentration has risen, indicating improved corrosion inhibition effectiveness for safeguarding mild steel. This also suggests that the inhibitors' adsorption on the surface of the mild steel has also restricted the charge transfer process. The capacitive arc's larger diameter for CI@Zn-MOF compared to CI@Cd-MOF suggests that CI@Zn-MOF has a greater capability to prevent corrosion. The depression of the semicircle may be explained by the rough surface of the electrode surface or by the heterogeneity of the electrode surface at the microscopic level [14,73,74]. According to the Bode phase angle plot (Fig. 2 c and 3c) there are two times constants corresponding to double-layer capacitance at low frequency and film capacitance at moderately high frequency. Phase angle plots demonstrated a wider signal with an increase in the concentration of CI@Cd-MOF and CI@Zn-MOF, indicating the development of inhibitor’s film. Moreover, the phase angle increases with concentration and reaches its maximum at the highest concentration, 50 ppm, indicating that the inhibitor materials blocked the active sites on the mild steel surface and hindered corrosive element transfer [14,75].

As compared to the steel in NaCl medium alone, the addition of the inhibitors consistently lowers the current densities (vide 
                        Table 2
                        ). Inhibitors are classified as anodic, cathodic, or mixed according to the hindrance they impose on the reaction trail. It is possible to examine the mechanism of corrosion inhibition exhibited by the inhibitors by analyzing the corrosion potential (


                                 E

                                    corr



                        ). If there is a difference of more than 85 mV in the Ecorr values for an electrolyte with and without an inhibitor in the solution, the inhibitor is categorised as either a cathodic or anodic type inhibitor. If the aforementioned difference becomes less than 85 mV, the inhibitor is considered a mixed-type inhibitor [81]. Table 2 includes consequent corrosion potential (


                                 E

                                    corr



                        ) and corrosion current density (


                                 i

                                    corr



                        ). Experimental data showed that the difference in Ecorr values ​​between solutions with and without inhibitors was less than 85 mV. So the inhibitors have been categorised as mixed-type inhibitors. Both Ecorr and Icorr values revealed that the addition of inhibitors in the corrosive solutions retards both cathodic and anodic reaction happens in the electrochemical system. The drop in the Icorr value from 0.029 mA/cm2 (blank) to 0.001 mA/cm2 (50 ppm CI@Zn-MOF) suggests mild steel corrosion control owing to the presence of inhibitor. The 14.3 mV shift in Ecorr value towards a more negative potential (from −532.84 to −547.14 mV vs SCE) has demonstrated that the inhibitors act as a more cathodic kind of inhibitor [77,78]. Compared to the anodic Tafel slope, the cathodic Tafel slope changes more significantly. This demonstrates that the cathodic reaction (O2 reduction reaction) is more susceptible to control by the inhibitor's influence than the anodic reaction (metal dissolution) [77,78].

The Langmuir adsorption isotherm plot (vide 
                        Fig. 5
                        ) for the studied inhibitors exhibits a linear fit with a regression coefficient (R2) of 0.9991 (vide 
                        Table 3
                        ). Therefore it suggests that a uniform monolayer is formed by the inhibitors' adsorption on the metal surface [6,85].
